{"questionId":"13245","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The lengths of two of the sides in a triangle are 4 cm and 5 cm. Let <em>θ</em> be the angle between&nbsp;the two given sides. The triangle has an area of <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{{5\\sqrt {15} }}{2}\">\n  <mfrac>\n    <mrow>\n      <mn>5</mn>\n      <msqrt>\n        <mn>15</mn>\n      </msqrt>\n    </mrow>\n    <mn>2</mn>\n  </mfrac>\n</math></span> cm<sup>2</sup>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the two possible values for the length of the third side.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>let the third side be <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"x\">\n  <mi>x</mi>\n</math></span></p>\n<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{x^2} = {4^2} + {5^2} - 2 \\times 4 \\times 5 \\times {\\text{cos}}\\,\\theta \">\n  <mrow>\n    <msup>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>2</mn>\n    </msup>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mrow>\n    <msup>\n      <mn>4</mn>\n      <mn>2</mn>\n    </msup>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>+</mo>\n  <mrow>\n    <msup>\n      <mn>5</mn>\n      <mn>2</mn>\n    </msup>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>−</mo>\n  <mn>2</mn>\n  <mo>×</mo>\n  <mn>4</mn>\n  <mo>×</mo>\n  <mn>5</mn>\n  <mo>×</mo>\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>cos</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n  <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace>\n  <mi>θ</mi>\n</math></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>M1</strong></em></p>\n<p>valid attempt to find&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{\\text{cos}}\\,\\theta \">\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>cos</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n  <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace>\n  <mi>θ</mi>\n</math></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Do not accept writing&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{\\text{cos}}\\left( {{\\text{arcsin}}\\left( {\\frac{{\\sqrt {15} }}{4}} \\right)} \\right)\">\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>cos</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n  <mrow>\n    <mo>(</mo>\n    <mrow>\n      <mrow>\n        <mtext>arcsin</mtext>\n      </mrow>\n      <mrow>\n        <mo>(</mo>\n        <mrow>\n          <mfrac>\n            <mrow>\n              <msqrt>\n                <mn>15</mn>\n              </msqrt>\n            </mrow>\n            <mn>4</mn>\n          </mfrac>\n        </mrow>\n        <mo>)</mo>\n      </mrow>\n    </mrow>\n    <mo>)</mo>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span> as a valid method.</p>\n<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{\\text{cos}}\\,\\theta = \\pm \\sqrt {1 - \\frac{{15}}{{16}}} \">\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>cos</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n  <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace>\n  <mi>θ</mi>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mo>±</mo>\n  <msqrt>\n    <mn>1</mn>\n    <mo>−</mo>\n    <mfrac>\n      <mrow>\n        <mn>15</mn>\n      </mrow>\n      <mrow>\n        <mn>16</mn>\n      </mrow>\n    </mfrac>\n  </msqrt>\n</math></span></p>\n<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\" = \\frac{1}{4}{\\text{,}}\\,\\, - \\frac{1}{4}\">\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mfrac>\n    <mn>1</mn>\n    <mn>4</mn>\n  </mfrac>\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>,</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n  <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace>\n  <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace>\n  <mo>−</mo>\n  <mfrac>\n    <mn>1</mn>\n    <mn>4</mn>\n  </mfrac>\n</math></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em><em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{x^2} = 16 + 25 - 2 \\times 4 \\times 5 \\times&nbsp; \\pm \\frac{1}{4}\">\n  <mrow>\n    <msup>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>2</mn>\n    </msup>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mn>16</mn>\n  <mo>+</mo>\n  <mn>25</mn>\n  <mo>−</mo>\n  <mn>2</mn>\n  <mo>×</mo>\n  <mn>4</mn>\n  <mo>×</mo>\n  <mn>5</mn>\n  <mo>×</mo>\n  <mo>±</mo>\n  <mfrac>\n    <mn>1</mn>\n    <mn>4</mn>\n  </mfrac>\n</math></span></p>\n<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"x = \\sqrt {31} \">\n  <mi>x</mi>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <msqrt>\n    <mn>31</mn>\n  </msqrt>\n</math></span>&nbsp; or&nbsp;&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\sqrt {51} \">\n  <msqrt>\n    <mn>51</mn>\n  </msqrt>\n</math></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em><em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong>[6 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"13245","referenceCode":"19M.1.AHL.TZ1.H_4b","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Find the two possible values for the length of the third side.","paper":"1","level":"HL","questionNumber":"b","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 6]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.2—2d and 3d trig, sine rule, cosine rule, area","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.5—Unit circle definitions of sin, cos, tan. Exact trig ratios, ambiguous case of sine rule"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}